                          \
    The other day I finished Attack on Titan, and now I finished Cowboy Bebop... two amazing anime, drawn quite differently, yet both powerful in its own way. You want to see an anime that's highly mature, characterized, even philosophical? One of the rare gems whose English dub is perhaps superior to the sub? This is only the second I've seen dubbed, after Fullmetal Alchemist: Brotherhood. You want to see a troubled character, and wonder yourself about your purpose in life? Existentialism. Loneliness. The power of silence.\
Cowboy Bebop is episodic -- that is, most of the episodes have their own short stories. But that's to be\
          \
        expected, given the nature of the characters. You can criticize Bebop all you want for this, but hey, an anime's setting and characters produce the plot. Bleach, for example. You could say that it's extremely elongated and contains too much combat, but as practically all of the main characters are fighters (whether Shinigami or not) and Soul Society is protected by squads of fighters, and they fight Hollows and other variations, combat just has to run the show. Bleach can't be as character-focused as Clannad or plot-developed as FMAB. Cowboy Bebop is about bounty hunters, and you can't have a series about just finding one or two bad guys. If you want to reveal more about the bounty hunter life and delve more deeply into the futuristic world, then having the crew go after multiple bounties is just natural. So if you're thrown off by that, I can't blame you, but nevertheless you must try it out. Like Attack on Titan, Bebop performs magnificently with progressive revelation, but this time into the characters' pasts. One of the (many) superb facets of anime is the hidden past of a character. Here the pasts continue to haunt the characters, especially Spike Spiegel, the protagonist. As you watch more and more of Bebop, you see more and more of the main characters' pasts and empathize more with them.\
As I mentioned before, loneliness. Spike is such an awesome character. I mean, I've seen some pretty awesome characters -- Natsu Dragneel, Ichigo Kurosaki, Tomoya Okazaki, Toshiro Hitsugaya, Lelouch, Light Yagami, etc. But Spike just beats them all. Besides his skill in hand-to-hand combat and outwitting his enemies, he is someone so influenced by the past. Take the impact of Simba's past from The Lion King and put it on steroids. Simba had the whole \"you can't change the past\" thing, right? Exactly what happens with Spike. Why is he so nonchalant? Why does he go towards danger so rashly? Not because he's cool (well, that too), but because he has already died to him. I won't explain more, perhaps I've said too much already. He is such a complex person. The character development -- or rather, revelation -- of Spike Spiegel alone gives the characterization in Bebop a 10.\
The art of Bebop is from 1998, so it's quite different from anything more recent. But I think the older styles are better in that they can show more depth, more hue to the setting and characters. The way cigar smoke billows into the air. How flashbacks are tinged with a sad grey. Whenever Spike fights. If Bebop were animated by, say, Bones after the style of FMAB, it would be different. After seeing Bebop, I am more motivated to continue watching Neon Genesis Evangelion, to see more of that art style.\
The opening by The Seatbelts has panache, elan, style. The ending is sorrowful, grey, morose. Take the two of them together and you have the character of Spike -- outwardly easygoing and jaunty, but inwardly conflicted. The soundtrack is jazz, and can range into all the necessary emotions. Heck, the music of Cowboy Bebop has its own Wikipedia page.\
The only reason why I gave Enjoyment a 9 out of 10 is because while I enjoyed each episode, I was not captivated the whole time, that is, I did not rush to finish the show in one run. This is one of those shows that you enjoy more as you watch, and after you finish and come to realize the awesomeness of the series. Up to the last episode, the strings are all pulled together and there is a resolution. It's one of those endings that you may not think you want, but it's the ending necessary for the story.\
In my top 5, without a doubt.\
