    I'm still trying to get a full and complete understanding of everything under the umbrella of existentialism, but in the meantime here's my review of Cowboy Bebop. Throughout the summer I had been watching some mediocre anime, and I was in somewhat of a slump in terms of enjoyment. It may have been from a lack of philosophy or really enjoyable plot, but after being in such a slump, Cowboy Bebop was a breath of fresh air. I don't normally enjoy(and would almost borderline say that nothing pisses me off more than) episodic anime, but despite some personal issues with the way it ran and\
          \
        its formula, Cowboy Bebop overall was a really enjoyable show. The show stands out amid a lot of anime and is aimed at western audiences and feels a bit like the musical Chicago mixed with Star Wars if Spike Spiegel himself kicked John Williams in the nads and told him to rewrite the music into jazz and told George Lucas to stop making prequels. So first, the technical stuff of the show is understandable given the shows age, but also stood out in some brilliant ways. To my knowledge, Cowboy Bebop was made in the 90's so the animation is good, but does look aged by today's standards. However in terms of the bells and whistles of the show, the music (OH THE MUSIC) was what really stood out in terms of what made the show \"pop\" I guess.On top of all the technical aesthetics, the characters and life contemplation dialogue were really the draw for me AND the best parts of the show. Each character has a ton of personality, and while each of their backstories aren't completely delivered or are delivered at somewhat of a sloppy pace, Spike, Jet, Ed, and Faye's diverse presences all add a little flavor of their own to the crew and the show in general. Their personalities are realistic, as each crew member of the Bebop is based on past actions and consequences, and this is the recurring and underlying theme throughout the whole show; the past and its effect on the present and future. The situations they are put in vary too, from hunting bounties, looking at their pasts or fighting old food makes the show somewhat of a grab bag feel. On one hand it's great because it lets the viewer wander into the wonders that science fiction holds (especially the episodes about computer hacking, saving the rat-fish things, and the one about the out of body A.I. religion). It's good because episode plots and focuses may be different, but it's a formula that didn't quite click with me. While each episode is enjoyable, I wasn't left with a sense of accomplishment after every single one. You never see what the characters do with the money they get from bounties and in some of the situations if feels like they should learn something and grow a bit from their adventures, but while having personality, all the characters are surprisingly static throughout the course of the show. The lack of character development is a personal gripe but given the fact that it's a show about holding onto the past as a main theme, I felt a little jipped. The episodic nature of the show made it hard to relate to Julia, Spike and Vicious' relationships because the show didn't focus on it quite enough and just kinda teased me with it at the beginning and crammed it in just to resolve it during the last couple episodes. The whole Red Dragon Syndicate subplot felt like it should have been touched on more since it was such an important part of the show. My final gripe with it is if the show is that the setting was fascinating, but the ruined planet Earth and the cramped urban space cities could have had more of a message of humanity's past about it. The entire solar system being the way it was is a fascinating concept, but was just kinda shoved in the corner and never fully got to shine, and I really wanted it to. But while those might seem like personal problems, the show also affected me personally. At times, the show makes you think about your own life with its themes and even sweetly pokes at the soul. Seriously my eyes got a little watery during Ed and Ein's final scene. So despite some issues that the show may have, a lot of the entertainment value is held in the ragtag crew's personal issues and how they get through the struggles presented in each episode. So I'd recommend this anime more for the adult crowd and science ficiton lovers because of it's deep content, and I gotta say I was really impressed overall. See you space cowboy.\
